{{EngvarB|date=August 2016}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}} {{Infobox person |name = Alex Vella |image = |caption = |birth_name = Alessio Emmanuel Vella |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1953|6|5|df=y}} |birth_place = {{flag|Malta}} |death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> |death_place = |alias = Maltese Falcon |occupation = Biker, lightweight boxer |known_for = Former National President of the [[Rebels MC]], founder of the Sydney chapter |spouse = [[Heather Vella]] |children = [[Alex Vella Jr.]] |website = {{URL|alexvella.com.au}} }}
'''Alessio Emmanuel "Alex" Vella''' (born 5 June 1953), or '''Maltese Falcon''', is a Maltese businessman, former boxer, stand over man and the former National President of the [[Rebels Motorcycle Club]] in Australia. Despite having lived in Australia since the 1960s, he is not a citizen of the country.<ref name=abc-no-appeal /> This caused [[Visa (document)|visa]] problems when he tried to return to Australia after having gone to Japan with his son [[Adam Vella (boxer)|Adam]] (also a boxer) for a boxing match in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwwildcats.net/yabb/YaBB.pl?num=1174517431 |title=Rebels boss stranded in Japan |publisher=Ldcats.net |date= |accessdate=10 October 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008122945/http://wwwildcats.net/yabb/YaBB.pl?num=1174517431 |archivedate=8 October 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/bikie-leader-stranded-in-japan/2007/03/22/1174153218161.html |title=Bikie leader stranded in Japan |publisher=Theage.com.au |date=22 March 2007 |agency=AAP|accessdate=10 October 2011}}</ref> The [[New South Wales Police Force]] tried to bar Vella from re-entering Australia then, but he was eventually allowed to return.<ref>{{cite web |first=Dylan |last=Welch |date=4 April 2007 |work=Sydney Morning Herald |url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/bikie-gang-rebel-allowed-back-in/2007/04/04/1175366279726.html?page=1 |title=Bikie gang rebel back |accessdate=10 October 2011}}</ref> In 2014 Vella visited his friends in family in Malta, and while he was there, his residency visa was cancelled by the Australian [[Minister for Immigration and Border Protection]]. Vella tried to appeal in the High Court in October 2015, but was not permitted to.
== Private life == Vella was born into a strict [[Catholicism|Catholic]] family in [[Malta]] and was one of eleven children. His parents lived in a small villa near Buskett. He began work at the age of eight, carrying buckets of water on a building site for 30 cents a day, and is functionally illiterate. He and his family then moved to Australia in the 1960s and established a strawberry farm near [[Horsley Park, New South Wales]]. In his 20s, he sometimes worked two or three jobs at a time; as a [[bouncer (doorman)|bouncer]], [[labourer]] and [[bricklayer]]. He also joined the Rebels Motorcycle Club while pursuing a promising career as a [[Boxing|boxer]]; he eventually became the Maltese light-heavyweight champion. After a serious road accident, he received {{AUD|link=yes|225,000}} in compensation and used this money to set up a business importing and selling motorcycles.
== Legal issues == In 1990, police found a $15,000 stash of [[marijuana]] while searching his home, which they believed to be a [[methamphetamine]] factory. He received a fairly light sentence: 18-months of two-nights-a-week prison, and two-days-a-week community service. He has also been arrested, but not convicted, of a number of other crimes including stabbing two men and assaulting a woman. He was freed on appeal after being given six months in jail for the latter.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hills |first=Ben |url=http://benhills.com/articles/scams-scoundrels/the-millionaire-bikie/ |title=Alex Vella, the millionaire bikie |publisher=Benhills.com |date= |accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref>
On 28 May 2008, Vella won a court case against the [[ANZ Bank]]. He sued them for $2.7&nbsp;million after his former business partner, Tony Caradonna, re-mortgaged three properties, including the Rebels' clubhouse, for $2.4&nbsp;million by falsifying Vella's signature.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theage.com.au/business/bikie-boss-wins-24m-fraud-case-20080528-2iv1.html |title=Bikie boss wins $2.4m fraud case | newspaper=The Age |date=28 May 2008 |accessdate=21 May 2018 |agency=AAP}}</ref> He also claimed $300,000 was fraudulently withdrawn from their joint bank account.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/05/28/2257868.htm?site=sydney |title=Head of the Rebels bikie gang wins multi-million-dollar lawsuit against ANZ Bank |publisher=Abc.net.au |date=28 May 2008 |accessdate=10 October 2011}}</ref>
On 16 June 2014, Immigration Minister [[Scott Morrison]] cancelled Vella's residency visa on character grounds while Vella was visiting Malta.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/minister-revokes-rebels-bikie-boss-alex-vellas-visa-while-overseas/story-fni0fiyv-1226956327257 |title=Minister revokes Rebels bikie boss Alex Vella's visa while overseas |publisher=heraldsun.com.au |date=16 June 2014 |accessdate=16 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-06-17/rebel-bikie-gang-leaders-visa-cancelled/5528744|title=Government cancels Rebel bikie gang leader Alex Vella's visa|publisher=ABC (Australia) |date=17 June 2014|accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref> Vella attempted to challenge the action in the [[High Court of Australia]],<ref name=abc-last-ditch>{{cite news |last1=Willacy|first1=Mark |author-link=Mark Willacy |title=Rebels boss Alex Vella, stranded in Malta, launches last-ditch bid to return to Australia |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-10-16/exiled-rebels-boss-in-last-ditch-bid-to-return-to-australia/6854902 |accessdate=17 October 2015 |work=ABC News |publisher=ABC (Australia) |date=16 October 2015}}</ref> but on 16 October 2015 the court refused his application for [[leave to appeal]].<ref name=abc-no-appeal>{{cite news |title=Rebels Motorcycle Club boss Alex Vella loses bid to return to Australia |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-10-16/rebels-motorcycle-club-boss-alex-vella-loses-appeal/6860170 |accessdate=17 October 2015 |work=ABC News |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=16 October 2015}}</ref>
