{{Orphan|date=June 2018}}
'''Mahmud Dantata''' (1922–1983) was a Nigerian businessmen and politician who represented Kano East under the platform of [[Northern People's Congress|NPC]] in the Nigerian House of Representatives from 1965 to 1966.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Light|first1=Ivan H.|title=Ethnic enterprise in America : business and welfare among Chinese, Japanese and Blacks|date=1972|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=9780520024854|page=312|edition=3. pr.}}</ref> Dantata was originally sympathetic to the cause of the opposition party NEPU, led by Aminu Kano but after an incarceration, he aligned with the dominant party to defeat Aminu Kano for a seat in the House of Representatives in 1964.
==Life== Dantata was born in the Sareri quarters of [[Kano]] in 1922. The son of [[Alhassan Dantata]], a wealthy merchant, Dantata completed his formal education at Achimota College, in Ghana. Thereafter, he joined his father's business in 1945. In 1949, he branched out on his own, setting up investments in an hotel, sugar mill and petrol stations. His hotel was built in Koki quarters of Kano, a predominantly Muslim quarters where earlier attempts to build an hotel had been rejected. By 1951, he started exploring ways to transport pilgrims by road through Sudan to Saudi Arabia. He co-founded a pilgrimage business which was known as West African Pilgrimage Association (WAPA), and acquired buses for the transportation of pilgrims. A year later, he started a chartered flight service to transport pilgrims from Kano. In the Fagge quarters of Kano, he reclaimed a swampy land to build WAPA house, the area later became known for currency trading. Dantata himself soon dedicated a section of his business to currency trading.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hashim|first1=Yahaya|last2=Meagher|first2=Kate|title=Cross-border trade and the parallel currency market - trade and finance in the context of structural adjustment : a case study from Kano, Nigeria : [a report from the research programme The Political and Social Context of Structural Adjustment in Africa]|date=1999|publisher=Nordiska Afrikainstitutet|location=Uppsala|isbn=9171064494|page=30}}</ref>
In 1957, he was charged with illegal printing of currency notes, he was found guilty and sentenced to 8 years imprisonment. After his release, he switched political allegiance to NPC and won a parliamentary election to represent Kano East. In 1967, WAPA house diversified into lodging, night club and cinema and the businesses where managed by Sabo Bakin Zuwo who later became Kano state's governor in 1983.
